HOUSE RESOLUTION NO. 322
BY REPRESENTATIVES BRYANT AND KNOX
A RESOLUTION
To create the Task Force on Sentencing for Second Degree Murder to determine the best
changes to sentencing for second degree murder.
WHEREAS, second degree murder in Louisiana under R.S. 14:30.1 includes a
homicide committed with the specific intent to kill or inflict great bodily harm and a
homicide committed without intent during the perpetration or attempted perpetration of
certain enumerated felonies, commonly referred to as the "felony murder" doctrine; and
WHEREAS, pursuant to R.S. 14:30.1(B), a conviction for second degree murder
carries a mandatory, non-discretionary penalty of life imprisonment at hard labor without
benefit of parole, probation, or suspension of sentence; and
WHEREAS, in many other jurisdictions across the United States, a homicide
committed with specific intent or under the felony murder doctrine is classified as first
degree murder, whereas second degree murder frequently encompasses lower grades of
intent or lacks a mandatory sentence of life without parole eligibility; and
WHEREAS, a comprehensive evaluation is necessary to determine whether
Louisiana's second degree murder framework conceptually aligns with the legal definitions
utilized nationally, and to understand the specific historical and legal justifications for
applying a mandatory life sentence without parole eligibility to this category of offense; and
WHEREAS, there is currently a lack of centralized, empirical data indicating how
many second degree murder indictments and convictions within this state proceed under a
specific intent theory versus a felony murder theory; and
WHEREAS, analyzing the exact volume and proportion of cases prosecuted under
the felony murder doctrine is vital for the legislature to make informed, data-driven policy
decisions regarding sentencing that is proportional to the offense.
